title: application-gateway-end-to-end-ssl-powershell
content:
# Configure end-to-end TLS with Azure Application Gateway

This documentation explains how to configure end-to-end TLS with Azure Application Gateway using PowerShell.

## Overview

Azure Application Gateway supports end-to-end encryption of traffic. It terminates the TLS/SSL connection at the gateway and then applies routing rules to the traffic. The packet is re-encrypted and forwarded to the appropriate backend server based on the defined routing rules. Any response from the web server goes through the same process back to the end user.

Application Gateway offers custom TLS options and the ability to disable specific protocol versions such as TLSv1.0, TLSv1.1, and TLSv1.2. It also allows you to define the preferred cipher suites. To learn more about configurable TLS options, refer to the [TLS policy overview](application-gateway-SSL-policy-overview.md).

> [!NOTE]
> SSL 2.0 and SSL 3.0 are disabled by default and cannot be enabled. They are considered unsecure and cannot be used with Application Gateway.

![scenario image][scenario]

## Scenario

In this scenario, you will learn how to create an application gateway using end-to-end TLS with PowerShell.

This scenario will:

- Create a resource group named **appgw-rg**.
- Create a virtual network named **appgwvnet** with an address space of **10.0.0.0/16**.
- Create two subnets called **appgwsubnet** and **appsubnet**.
- Create a small application gateway supporting end-to-end TLS encryption that limits TLS protocol versions and cipher suites.

## Before you begin

Make sure you have the latest Azure PowerShell module installed. If not, you can install it by following the instructions in the [Azure PowerShell documentation](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/azure/new-azureps-module-az?view=azps-10.0.0).

To configure end-to-end TLS with an application gateway, you will need a certificate for the gateway and certificates for the backend servers. The gateway certificate is used to derive a symmetric key as per the TLS protocol specification. This symmetric key is then used to encrypt and decrypt the traffic sent to the gateway. The gateway certificate should be in Personal Information Exchange (PFX) format, which allows exporting the private key required by the application gateway for encryption and decryption.

To ensure end-to-end TLS encryption, the backend must be explicitly allowed by the application gateway. Upload the public certificate of the backend servers to the application gateway. This ensures that the application gateway only communicates with known backend instances, enhancing the security of the end-to-end communication.

The following sections describe the configuration process.

## Create the resource group

To create a resource group that contains the application gateway, follow these steps:

1. Sign in to your Azure account.

   ```powershell
   Connect-AzAccount
   ```

2. Select the subscription to use for this scenario.

   ```powershell
   Select-Azsubscription -SubscriptionName "<Subscription name>"
   ```

3. Create a resource group. (Skip this step if you're using an existing resource group.)

   ```powershell
   New-AzResourceGroup -Name appgw-rg -Location "West US"
   ```

## Create a virtual network and a subnet for the application gateway

To create a virtual network and two subnets, with one for the application gateway and the other for the backend web application, follow these steps:

1. Assign an address range for the subnet to be used for the application gateway.

   ```powershell
   $gwSubnet = New-AzVirtualNetworkSubnetConfig -Name 'appgwsubnet' -AddressPrefix 10.0.0.0/24
   ```

   > [!NOTE]
   > Subnets configured for an application gateway should be properly sized based on expected traffic and capacity needs.

As the documentation continues, it provides more detailed steps and code snippets to configure the application gateway with end-to-end TLS using PowerShell. It covers topics such as creating a public IP address, creating a backend pool, configuring HTTP settings, and enabling end-to-end TLS encryption. The documentation also includes additional information on troubleshooting and managing the application gateway.

**NOTE:** This document discusses configuration through the Azure Portal. Please _always_ use infrastructure-as-code (IaC) for production environments and deploy through Azure DevOps pipelines.
